{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"4deefd11-267a-4c56-8f2d-4abba9405d3f","content":"For a .NET Web API, use the `dotnet new webapi` template. Authentication options include:\n\n| Option | Flag |\n|---|---|\n| None (default) | `--auth None` |\n| Individual accounts | `--auth Individual` |\n| Microsoft identity platform | `--auth SingleOrg` |\n| Windows auth | `--auth Windows` |\n\n**Examples:**\n\n```bash\n# Basic API with JWT bearer auth (individual accounts)\ndotnet new webapi --auth Individual -o MyApi\n\n# API with Azure AD / Entra ID auth\ndotnet new webapi --auth SingleOrg --domain yourdomain.com -o MyApi\n```\n\nRun `dotnet new webapi --help` to see all options including HTTPS, OpenAPI, and framework version flags.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"e93bdee2-4aab-49cd-8e3a-1896e2083e2c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about web API project templates and authentication options. This is a general knowledge question about .NET (likely, given the repository context with dotnet plugins). I can answer this from my knowledge without needing to look at files.\n\nLet me provide a concise answer about dotnet web API templates and authentication options.","outputTokens":262,"requestId":"FBC0:27EBC3:173DA75:1A60635:69FE857A"},"id":"fa7d02c6-f36b-48f0-8f2b-e13b0d86fe88","timestamp":"2026-05-09T00:53:21.678Z","parentId":"4d974f67-5f46-4f31-81c8-147906f5c593"}
